<font color="#FF0000">ARE WE ON THE SAME WAVELENGTH?</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jun 10  2:03:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br>
    Your response sidesteps the concerns of those of us that found your language to extreme or provocative.  My reference to Limbaugh had NOTHING to do with listening to others' opinions and EVERYTHING to do with impugning others' motives. Your opening statement above still does not justify the terms you use.  Whether you like it or not, Congressmen are human beings too, in many varieties.<br><br>
    I wonder just how serious you are about getting support for your position.  You seem to be more concerned about just picking a fight with all of us.<br><br>
    As for the American Legion; I was a square peg over 3 years of membership.  Never felt comfortable with their politics, or with pushing &quot;Americanism&quot;.  Don't believe its what Jefferson or Madison had in mind.  <br><br>
    One historical correction, &quot;divine right of kings&quot; in England and its colonies died with Charles I 125 years before the First Continental Congress.  The principle of &quot;no man is above the law, even the king&quot; was first fully articulated by Justice Sir Edward Coke back in 1608 and 1610. The actual problem in the American Colonies was a Parliament that refused to consider its colonists full citizens entitled to a say in the government of the nation.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


